''System Shock 2'' received over a dozen awards, including seven "[[Game of the Year]]" awards by publications, such as [[Game Revolution]] and [[USA Today]].<ref name = "SS2 official awards">{{cite web | url = http://www.irrationalgames.com/shock2/ | title = System Shock 2 Official Website | publisher = [[Irrational Games]] | year = 2005 | accessdate = 2008-02-18}}</ref> Reviews were very positive and applauded the title for its hybrid gameplay, moody sound design, and engaging story.<ref name = "Metacritic SS2"/> Despite critical acclaim, the title failed to meet commercial sales expectations.<ref name = "1UP ss2"/> 

Many publications praised the title for its open-ended gameplay. With regard to character customization, [[IGN]] stated, <U+201C>The great thing about this system is that it allows you to play the game as completely different characters which gives the game an entirely different feel."<ref name = "IGN SS2 review"/> Erik Reckase writing for Just Adventure agreed, saying <U+201C>There are very few games that allow you [to] play the way you want to<U+201D>.<ref name = "JA ss2 review">{{cite web | url = http://www.justadventure.com/reviews/SS2/SS2.shtm | title = Review: System Shock 2 | author = Reckase, Erik | publisher = Just Adventure | accessdate = 2008-02-16}}</ref> Alec Norands of [[Allgame]] found the gameplay <U+201C>diverse enough to demand instant replayability.<ref name = "allgame ss2"/>

Critics described the game as quite frightening. Colin of [[Game Revolution]] attested that the game rivaled the terror of ''[[Resident Evil 2]]'' and ''[[Silent Hill]]'', stating "this game is brimming with horror<U+201D>.<ref name = "GameRev SS2"/>  ''[[Computer and Video Games| CVG]]'' described the atmosphere as <U+201C>gripping<U+201D> and guaranteed readers they would "jump out of [their] skin on more than one occasion<U+201D>.<ref name = "cvg review"/> Norands found the [[sound design]] particularly effective, calling it <U+201C>absolutely, teeth-clenchingly disturbing,<U+201D><ref name = "allgame ss2"/> while ''[[PC Gamer]]'' editor, William Harms, christened ''System Shock 2'' <U+201C>the most unsettling and frightening game [he had] ever played.<U+201D><ref name = "pc gamer ss2"/>

One of the most common criticisms centered on the weapon degradation system, which causes weapons to wear out and eventually break through excessive use. The system was designed to add tension by making the player consider his ammunition reserve.<ref name = "Gamespot SS2 Retrospect"/> Despite this, many critics found it to be annoying.<ref name = "IGN SS2 review"/><ref name = "1UP ss2"/><ref name = "allgame ss2"/> Members of the development team have also expressed misgivings about the system.<ref name = "Gamespot SS2 Retrospect">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/pc/rpg/systemshock2/video/6109962/system-shock-2-retrospective-interview | title = Gamespot Video: System Shock 2 Retrospective Interview | author = Gamespot Staff | publisher = [[GameSpot]] | date = 2004-10-04 | accessdate = 2008-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://xemu.blogharbor.com/blog/_archives/2004/10/5/154992.html | title = SS2: When Not Enough is Too Much | author = Fermier, Rob "Xemu" | date = 2004-10-05 | accessdate = 2006-08-23}} ''Rob Fermier was one of the lead programmers working on System Shock 2''.</ref> A patch was later released, allowing the player to control the degradation rate or disable it altogether.<ref name = "ss2 patch"/> 

The RPG system was another point of contention. Desslock of GameSpot described the job system as "badly unbalanced" due to the player's ability to develop any skills, regardless of their career choice.<ref name = "Gamespot SS2 review"/>  Norands felt similarly about the system, saying it "leaned towards a hacker character".<ref name = "allgame ss2"/>

== Legacy ==
''System Shock 2'' is regarded by some as highly influential, particularly on [[first-person shooter]]s. In a retrospective article, [[Gamespot]] declared the title "well ahead of its time" and stated it "upped the ante in dramatic and mechanical terms, creating an utterly engrossing, terrifying gameplay experience". Along with [[Deus Ex]], [[GamePro]] christened ''System Shock 2'' one of the "twin barrels of modern FPS innovation", due to its "deep and intricate role-playing gameplay".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.games.net/article/netten/1/112821/the-10-most-important-modern-shooters/ | title = The 10 Most Important Modern Shooters | first = Sid | last = Shuman | publisher = ''[[GamePro]]'' | accessdate = 2008-06-18}}</ref> IGN referred to the game as "another reinvention of the [[first person shooter | FPS]] genre...Story-driven, with great characters and a number of RPG elements, ''System Shock 2'' was a game that had you on the edge of your seat."<ref name = "IGNretro">{{cite web | url = http://retro.ign.com/articles/845/845533p1.html | title = Top 10 Retro DLC Games Wishlist | publisher = [[IGN]] | last = Shea | first = Cam | date = 2008-01-16 | accessdate = 2009-02-03}}</ref> The title has been inducted into a number of features listing the greatest games ever made, including ones by [[Gamespy]],<ref name = "gamespy greatest">{{ cite web | url = http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july01/top502ase/index3.shtm | title = GameSpy's Top 50 Games of All Time | author = GameSpy Staff | publisher = [[GameSpy]] | date = 2001-06-01 | accessdate = 2008-04-08 }}</ref> ''[[Edge (magazine) | Edge]]'',<ref name = "edge best game">{{ cite web | url = http://www.edge-online.com/magazine/edges-top-100-games-of-all-time?page=0,3 | title = EDGE'S TOP 100 GAMES OF ALL TIME | author = ''Edge'' Staff | publisher = ''[[Next Generation Magazine]]'' | date = 2007-07-02 | accessdate = 2008-04-08 }}</ref> [[IGN]],<ref name = "IGN top 100 games 2007 SS2"/> and Gamespot.<ref name = "Gamespot Greatest Game"/>

The return of SHODAN has been observed as an innovation itself. Gamespot described her revelation to the player as "one of the most shocking and effective video game plot devices [they had] ever encountered."<ref name = "Gamespot Greatest Game"/> Gamespy stated, that with SHODAN's inclusion ''System Shock 2'' "really became a complete experience instead of just another game."<ref name = "gamespy greatest"/> SHODAN has proven to be a popular character among some critics; among these are IGN,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pc.ign.com/articles/694/694399p1.html | title = IGN: Top Ten Tuesday: Most Memorable villains | author = IGN Staff | publisher = [[IGN]] | date = 2006-05-07 | accessdate = 2008-02-19}}</ref> Gamespot,<ref name = "gamespot shodan">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/features/tenspot_villains/page10.html | title = The Ten Best Computer Game Villains | author = GameSpot Staff | publisher = [[GameSpot]] | accessdate = 2008-06-11}}</ref> and [[The Phoenix (newspaper) | the Phoenix]].<ref name = "thephoenix">{{cite web | url = http://thephoenix.com/Boston//RecRoom/24912-20-Greatest-Bosses-in-Video-Game-History-#1-/ | title = The 20 greatest bosses in video game history | author = Krpata, Mitch and Stewart, Ryan | publisher = ''[[The Phoenix (newspaper)| The Phoenix]]'' | date = 2006-10-23 | accessdate = 2008-06-11}}  {{cite web |url=http://thephoenix.com/article_ektid24912.aspx |title=Archived Page from August 11, 2007 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070811002045/http://thephoenix.com/article_ektid24912.aspx |archivedate=2007-08-11}}</ref> 

''System Shock 2'' has amassed a substantial cult following over the years. Many fans have demanded a sequel.<ref name = "IGN top 100 games 2007 SS2"/> Some fans are active in the modding community where collaborations to update the game's graphics take place. One graphical enhancement [[Mod (computer gaming)| mod]], entitled Rebirth, replaces many [[Low poly| low-polygonal]] [[3D modeling| models]] with high-quality ones.<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=52239 | title =  System Shock 2 reborn | author = Bramwell, Tom | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | date = 2003-06-05 | accessdate = 2008-04-07 }}</ref> Another mod, the Shock Texture Upgrade Project (SHTUP), significantly increases the [[image resolution | resolution]] of in-game [[Texture mapping | textures]].<ref name = "Gamespot Greatest Game"/> 

In 2007, [[2K Boston/2K Australia]]<U+2014>previously known as [[Irrational Games]]<U+2014>released a [[spiritual successor]] to the ''[[System Shock]]'' series, entitled ''[[BioShock]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/bioshock/707256p1.html | title = BioShock Preview | publisher = [[GameSpy]] | date = [[2006-05-10]] |accessdate = 2007-05-08}}</ref> The game takes place in an abandoned underwater [[utopia]]n community that has gone awry through the genetic modification of its populace. The game has been very successful commercially<ref name = "Take-Two Press Release">{{cite press release |url=http://ir.take2games.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=314411 |title=Take-Two Interactive Software, Inc. Reports Strong Second Quarter Fiscal 2008 Financial Results |publisher=[[Take-Two Interactive]] |date=2008-06-05 |accessdate=2008-06-06}}</ref> and critically.<ref name = "Metacritic Bioshock"/> ''BioShock'' shares many gameplay elements with ''System Shock 2'': reconstitution stations can be found allowing the player to be resurrected when death occurs; [[Hacker (computer security)| hacking]], ammo conservation, and exploration are integral parts of gameplay; and various powers may be acquired via plasmids, special abilities that function similarly to psionic powers in ''System Shock 2''.<ref name="multiple">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/pc/action/bioshock/news.html?page=1&sid=6150533&tag=result;title;0 | title=E3 06: ''BioShock'' Gameplay Demo Impressions | publisher = Gamespot | date=[[2006-05-10]]|accessdate = 2007-11-04 | author = Brad Shoemaker and Andrew Park }}</ref> The two titles also share similar plots and employ audio logs to reveal backstory.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=88881 | title = Bioshock: A Defence Article | first = Kieron | last = Gillen | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | date = 2007-12-06 | accessdate = 2008-06-13}}</ref>

On January 9, 2006, GameSpot reported that [[Electronic Arts]] had renewed its trademark protection on the ''System Shock'' name<ref name = "Gamespot EA trademark">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/pc/rpg/systemshock2/news.html?sid=6142113&mode=recent | title = EA files System Shock trademark | author = Sinclair, Brendan | publisher = [[GameSpot]] | date  = January 9, 2006 | accessdate = 2008-02-14}}</ref> leading to speculation that a ''System Shock 3'' might be under development.<ref name = "CVG SS2 revived">{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=132172 | title = System Shock Revived? | author = Houlihan, John | publisher = ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' | date = 2006-01-09 | accessdate = 2008-02-16}}</ref> Three days later, ''[[Computer and Video Games| CVG]]'' reported that a reliable source had come forward and confirmed the development of the purported title. EA UK made no comments when confronted with the information.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=132449 | title = System Shock 3 rumours gather pace | first = Bishop | last = Stuart | publisher = ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' | date = 2006-01-12 | accessdate = 2008-09-13}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer UK]]'' expanded these rumors further, stating EA had charged the team behind ''[[The Godfather (game)| The Godfather]]'' with developing ''System Shock 3''.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Eyewitness Undercover | author = ''PC Gamer UK Staff'' | publisher = ''[[PC Gamer UK]]'' | month = September | year = 2006 | accessdate = 2008-09-14}}</ref> Ken Levine, when asked whether he would helm a third installment, replied, "that question is completely out of my hands."<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamepro.com/article/news/121329/bioshock-ken-levine-talks-morality-system-shock-3-possibilities/ | title = BioShock: Ken Levine talks morality, System Shock 3 possibilities | author = ''GamePro'' | publisher = [[GamePro]] | date = 2007-07-12 | accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref> He expressed optimism at the prospect of ''System Shock 3'',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3153215 | title = Ken Levine: CGW Interviews the Man Behind Irrational from 1UP.com | first = Sean | last = Molloy | publisher = [[1Up.com]] | date = 2006-09-01 | accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref> but was also critical of EA's attitude towards development of the game.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=143616 | title = Levine: EA 'didn't give a sh*t' about Sys Shock 3 | author = Bishop, Stuart | publisher = ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' | date = 2006-07-31 | accessdate = 2008-02-17}}</ref><ref name = "Eurogamer Ken Levine">{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=66394 | title = BioShock dev slams EA | author = Bramwell, Tom | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | date = 2006-08-01 | accessdate = 2008-02-17}}</ref> As of January 2009, nothing conclusive has been reported regarding the status of the title.<ref name = "techspot21games">{{cite web | url = http://www.techspot.com/article/140-21-first-person-shooters/ | title = 21 First Person Shooters you shouldn't have missed | last = DeCarlo | first = Matthew | publisher = [[Techspot]] | date = 2009-01-19 | accessdate = 2009-02-03}}</ref>

